collection: ?Stroud Museum or in Private hands? But see other side.
site: England, gloucestershire,dudbridge (1 mile from stroud),dudbridge mills,found in a sewerage excavation in an orchard, embedded in lias clay, about 10 feet from the surface, at some time before the opening of the stroud museum.
associations: "In this particular bronze axe some fragments of wood were found, but unfortunately the [navey?] (the finder) brushed these out."
description: "It is a remarkably well-formed weapon. The edge is quite sharp, which may be accounted for by the fact of its having been enclosed in matrix of clay.",From the sketch, there appears to be three ridges down the face of the blade; prominent stop-ridge; and chips out of the cutting edge at the end nearer the loop, and from the edges of one of the side flanges.
publications: An account is given in a cutting from a local (Stroud) newspaper, of uncertain date (but about 1910 or 1911), which account also includes a drawing of the implement. For the relevant extracts, see other side.
remarks: For all known particulars, see other side.,From an old (undated, but 1910 or 1911) cutting from a Stroud newspaper, sent to the British Museum in January 1936 by the curator of Stroud Museum, to whom the cutting has been returned. The description and particulars on the face of this card are from the same cutting:,"We are indebted to Mr. John Bezant, specialist in the antique, of George Street, Stroud, for permission to illustrate a Bronze Celt or Battle Axe, recently found in a sewerage excavation in an orchard near Dudbridge Mills. The navey who found the ancient weapon was well advised in taking it to Mr. Brazant, because in addition to being a keen antiquariest, he is also anxious to witness the opening of the long-promised museum in Stroud, and although he has been made a valuable offer for this find, he has formed the resolution not to part with it until he has received assurance that it will eventually come to the local Museum...,A find would probably be there (i.e. at Dudbridge), as at Ryeford, as Celtic (sic) people who lived in Gloucestershire would naturally when moving from one hilly district to another select the most suitable spots in marshy lowlands for passing on to firmer ground." Here follows a dissertation on varieties of Celts from "Arms and Armour", and irrelevant remarks about Stone, Bronze, and Iron Ages, Romans, Gauls, etc.,The accompanying sketch is a copy of that accompanying the newspaper article.,Copy of covering letter from C. Gardiner of Stroud Museum, to the B.M., dated January 1, 1936: "When I got here some 6 years ago, I found the enclosed cutting. I pursued the bronze and I believe it was bought by a man who behaves badly and exiled himself to Maderia [?]. It is probably locked up in his house here, but though I  have written to him through his lawyer he does not reply. Still, the figure is probably enough to enable you to describe it in the list of English bronzes should you care to do so."

collection: Worthing Museum,54/440
description: Discovered by workmen digging a drainage inspection box immediately to the south of the front door of "Seaward", The Ridings, East Preston (TQ 068018). Found 18 inches deep in clay mould. Found July, 1954.,Late Bronze Age palstave with stop-ridge and loop. Two raised ribs below and almost at right angles to stop-ridge. Both flanges on one side damaged.
remarks: One of nine implements found at "Seaward" by workmen. This, and one small fragment of a palstave were brought to my notice at the Museum; extensive enquiries, however, failed to trace any others which were reputed to have been 'sold to a dealer for sixpence'; etc. The building firm concerned, also, was most un-cooperative. The workmen were questioned as to the appearance of the others and from their description it appears to have been a hoard of eight palstaves and one socketed axe.

collection: Hull Museum, No. 171
patina: Dark brown and green; a patch of bronze colour on butt, where patina has been cleaned off
surface: Rough and "lumpy" rear cutting-edge; and on the flanges; otherwise smooth, except for the cuts on the surface of the blade.
description: Cutting edge chipped and blunt; on each face of the blade are a number (?three) of ribs running down towards the cutting edge: those have almost disappeared except close to the stopridge. Very prominent stopridge. On each face between the flanges are three ribs, which appear to be more or less in the same sharpit[?] line as those on the blade. Flanges much worn down and broken. Butt broken off. There are traces of a flaw in the metal here, which probably caused this fracture: numbers of scratches and cuts near the cutting edge. Loop rather large and prominent.
remarks: Purchase by the Hull Museum in Sussex and said to have been part of a hoard found in Kent. With the purchase was a forged socketed celt said to have been found with the others, and this makes the find  place uncertain. The other members of this alleged hoard are Flanged Celt (Hull Museum 170) and Palstave (Hull Museum 169).
